Under Section 7 of the National Labor Relations Act (NLRA), employees are free to communicate—online as well as off-line—about “wages, hours, and other terms and conditions of employment.”  Consequently, an employer may not lawfully discipline or fire employees for social-media posts, e-mails, texts, blogs, etc., that:

• discuss or compare pay, bonuses, commissions, or benefits;  
• complain about or seek changes in work schedules, overtime, workload, staffing levels, or safety;  
• criticize supervisors or company policies in an effort to enlist co-workers’ support or bring problems to management’s attention;  
• encourage, plan, or comment on collective action such as signing a petition, talking to the press, or forming/joining a union.

These communications are treated as “protected concerted activity” under federal statute, so long as they are made on behalf of, or with the involvement of, other employees (or seek to induce such involvement) and are not so egregious—e.g., threats of violence, extreme harassment, or disclosure of proprietary trade secrets—that they lose the Act’s protection.
